Results of a model of delivering hepatitis C care in a homeless metropolitan population in England.
 Promoting education and having flexible and reflex "mobile" on-site-testing and treatment for HCV in the homeless population improves engagement with the healthcare system, meaning higher rates of treatment initiation and SVR. However, street-based homeless population not linked with harm reduction services are less likely to initiate HCV treatment, highlighting an urgent need for a broad health inclusion system.
